NAME
       ps - report a snapshot of the current processes

SYNOPSIS
       ps [options]

DESCRIPTION
       ps  displays  information  about a selection of the active processes.
       It supports UNIX, BSD, and GNU-style options.  UNIX options are
       preceded by a dash, BSD options are not, and GNU long options
       start with --.

   UNIX OPTIONS
       -e, -A select all processes

       -f     full-format listing

       -l     long format

       -o format
              user-defined format (comma-separated keywords)

       -p pidlist
              select by process ID

       -u userlist
              select by effective user ID or name

       -a     select all with a tty except session leaders

       -d     select all except session leaders

       -N, --deselect
              negate selection

       -r     select only running processes

       -T     select all processes with this terminal

       -x     include processes without a controlling terminal

   BSD OPTIONS
       a      select all processes with a terminal, or used with x to
              select all processes

       e      show the environment after the command

       x      select processes without controlling terminals

       u      display user-oriented format

       j      BSD job control format

       l      BSD long format

       s      signal format

       v      virtual memory format

   GNU LONG OPTIONS
       --forest
              display process tree (ASCII art hierarchy)

       --sort spec
              sorting order (+ ascending, - descending, e.g., --sort=-pcpu)

       --no-headers
              print no header line at all

       --headers
              repeat header lines, one per page of output

       --cols N, --columns N, --width N
              set screen width

       --rows N, --lines N
              set screen height

       --cumulative
              include dead child process data

       --help display this help and exit

       --version
              output version information and exit

   FORMAT KEYWORDS
       pid, ppid, pgid, sid, tty, stat, user, uid, pri, ni, vsz, rss,
       pcpu, pmem, time, etime, comm, args, wchan, start_time, tname,
       nlwp, psr, cls, flags

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if errors occurred

